<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,692,824]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Often one of the most abundant species found in shallow sandy areas of the major river systems in the Kimberley, the benthic 
<taxonomicName box="[282,507,728,752]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Glossogobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="giuris">
<emphasis box="[282,507,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Glossogobius giuris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread in the region (
<figureCitation box="[835,920,727,751]" captionStart="FIGURE 40" captionStartId="56.[151,250,1497,1520]" captionTargetBox="[262,1324,196,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-26@56.[258,1329,193,1476]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURE 40. Distribution of Glossogobius giuris in the Kimberley." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). The species is found throughout the Fitzroy, King Edward, Carson, Drysdale and Ord Rivers, with records from other systems being less extensive, including those from the May, Isdell, Prince Regent, Lawley, Durack and Pentecost Rivers.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
